    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2637097377" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2637097377" />
    <a title="Sonny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6696670-sonny"><img alt="Sonny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577449810p2/6696670.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2637097377?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sonny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sonny" href="/user/show/6696670-sonny">Sonny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780670859160" href="/book/show/952879.A_People_s_Tragedy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6696670-sonny?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6696670-sonny?shelf=russia">russia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2637097377" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6155501949208027702">Orlando Figes is a British academic, historian and writer known for his works on Russian history. The <i>Financial Times</i> has called Figes &quot;the great storyteller of modern Russian historians.&quot; His first major book, <i>A People&apos;s Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924</i>, was published in 1996. The book garnered several literary and history awards, winning the Wolfson History Prize, the WH Smith Literary Award, the NCR Book Award, the Longman/History Today Book Prize, and the Los Angeles Times Book Pri</span>
  <span id="freeText6155501949208027702" style="display:none">Orlando Figes is a British academic, historian and writer known for his works on Russian history. The <i>Financial Times</i> has called Figes "the great storyteller of modern Russian historians." His first major book, <i>A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924</i>, was published in 1996. The book garnered several literary and history awards, winning the Wolfson History Prize, the WH Smith Literary Award, the NCR Book Award, the Longman/History Today Book Prize, and the Los Angeles Times Book Prize. Figes’ knowledge of Russia is impressive, and he has written a brilliant history of the Russian Revolution. Elaborately researched and logically argued, the book presents a comprehensive view of one of the most important and complicated of modern events.<br /><br />In his book, Figes chronicles the history of the Russian Revolution from the devastating famine of 1891-1892 through to the death of Lenin in 1924, when "the basic elements of the Stalinist regime - the one-party state, the system of terror and the cult of the personality - were all in place". Figes begins with the great famine because it marked the beginning of both the peasant revolution and the awakening of the social conscience of the educated upper classes. It was the upper classes who then exerted pressure on the tsar to be more responsive to the people’s needs. A revolt of people in 1905 demanding an elected assembly forced the tsar to issue a manifesto on the establishment of a legislative Duma. This was followed, however, in 1906-07 by the failure of the dominant opposition party, the Constitutional Democrats—or Kadets—to compel the monarchy to accept a genuine constitution. The suicidal unwillingness of Tsar Nicholas to share power and his stubborn belief that his autocracy was divinely ordained is simply stunning. The failure of the Duma and the to benefit the peasants and workers through rule of law created a void that would eventually be occupied by the revolutionary parties. <br /><br /><i>“The Provisional Government was a government of persuasion. Not having been elected by the people, it depended largely on the power of the word to establish its authority. [The members of the Provisional Government] … believed that the primary duty of the February Revolution was to educate the people in their civic rights and duties.”</i><br />― Orlando Figes, A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924<br /> <br />However, it was World War I that opened the door to the revolutionaries completely. Peasants were mobilized by the millions to fight (and die) in the war, only to have it tragically mismanaged. Russia appeared headed for defeat. Hunger, cold, war, along with the czar’s refusal to share power and the Duma’s paralysis led to the February Revolution of 1917, when long-standing discontent with the monarchy erupted into mass protests against food rationing in Petrograd (present-day Saint Petersburg), then the capital of Russia. This discontent unexpectedly brought the monarchy down and confronted the Duma, now organized as a provisional government.<br /><br /><i>“For the Romanov regime fell under the weight of its own internal contradictions. It was not overthrown.”</i><br />― Orlando Figes, A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924<br /><br /><i>"With the Russian Empire teetering on the brink of collapse, the tsarist regime responded to the crises with its usual incompetence and obstinacy. The basic problem was that Nicholas himself remained totally oblivious to the extremity of the situation. While the country sank deeper into chaos he continued to fill his diary with terse and trivial notes on the weather, the company at tea and the number of birds he had shot that day. When Bulygin suggested that political concessions might be needed to calm the country, Nicholas was taken aback and told the Minister: 'One would think you are afraid a revolution will break out.' 'Your majesty,' came the reply, 'the revolution has already begun."</i><br />― Orlando Figes, A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924<br /><br />The Bolsheviks, a radical, far-left, and revolutionary Marxist faction founded by Vladimir Lenin, moved into this volatile situation. But the Bolshevik Party at the time was more of a restless mass movement than the monolithic organization, obedient to the leader’s commands, that it later became. The Bolsheviks seized power in October. Figes describes the Bolsheviks’ seizure of power in this way:<br /><br /><i>“There was of course no master plan to this—everything was improvised, as it had to be in a revolution—yet Lenin, at least, had an instinctive sense of the general direction, of what he himself called the ‘revolutionary dialectic,’ and in many ways that was the essence of his political genius. Local Soviet rule in the countryside, which was in effect the unfettered power of the village assembly to rule itself and divide the gentry’s land, would undermine the need for the [democratically elected] Constituent Assembly in the minds of the peasants and thus destroy the political base of the SRs [peasant-oriented socialists]. The exercise of ‘workers’ control’ through the factory committee would help to dismantle the old industrial infrastructure—what the Bolsheviks called the ‘capitalist system'—while shifting the blame for the industrial crises to the workers themselves [thus justifying party control]. The spread of soldiers’ power and of local peace initiatives at the front, which the Bolsheviks encouraged, would undermine the plans of the old army commanders to mobilize the troops against the new regime and restart the war. Eighty years earlier, the anarchist Michael Bakunin, drawing directly on Hegel, had put the same ‘revolutionary dialectic’ in an aphorism: ‘The desire to destroy is also a creative desire.’ ”</i><br />― Orlando Figes, A People's Tragedy: The Russian Revolution: 1891-1924<br /><br />The Bolshevik seizure of power led to a civil war with the Whites between 1918 and 1920, and the Bolsheviks’ revolution gave way to the dictatorial centralization of the new Soviet state. Factory committees were replaced by single managers monitored by the party. Soon all industry and commerce were nationalized and placed under the control of the Supreme Economic Council. Determined to avoid the fate of the Paris Commune, the Bolsheviks created a military dictatorship to combat peasant anarchy through the planned control of the industrial and agricultural economy. Figes maintains that the Bolsheviks came to power only by revolution, but they retained power only by centralizing it and ruthlessly using terror to wipe out opposition parties.<br /><br />Figes’ writing style seeks to balance important events with their impact on individuals—a style used to great effect by Max Hastings in his book <i>Inferno: The World at War, 1939-1945</i>. Figes balances the revolution's great personalities with the stories of a few individuals of average importance as a means of describing what real people did in the course of the revolution. Figes incorporates the diaries and letters of select individuals with the political narrative. This attention to the human aspect of the revolution allows us to see how the fabric of a society was ripped apart. Some examples include Prince George Lvov, leader of his zemstvo (elected local administration) who winds up with the Whites, only to die as an emigre in Paris. Also included is General Alexis Brusilov, who served the czar, then the provisional government and, finally, the Red Army. The proletarian writer and intellectual Maxim Gorky, who at one time closely associated himself with Vladimir Lenin, left Russia to escape the increasingly repressive atmosphere and eventually wound up a prisoner under Stalin. Figes also follows the peasant Semen Kanatchikov from the village to the factory, to Marxism and Bolshevism. <br /><br />While Figes gets high marks for his research, he is not a good enough writer to bring these people fully to life. At times, the book becomes monotonous. Another weakness of the book is Figes’ arrogance. While his book is an enormous accomplishment, he is at times overbearing, petty and patronizing. He writes as though his book were definitive. He is at his most outlandish when he argues small points with American academic and author Richard Pipes.<br /><br />The greatest contribution of Figes is to capture something of the sheer magnitude of the revolutionary force. He provides an extraordinary and comprehensive explanation not only of why the revolution occurred, but why it turned out the way it did. His insight into the Russian people is impressive. Another key contribution is his presentation of the revolution as destructive and debasing rather than as creative and liberating. Figes’ Russian Revolution thus turns out to be the tragedy of a people shaped by that people.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6155501949208027702" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

