<div id="review_1885612291" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1885612291" />
    <a title="Frank Stein" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1398873-frank-stein"><img alt="Frank Stein" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1248028137p2/1398873.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1885612291?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Frank Stein" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Frank Stein" href="/user/show/1398873-frank-stein">Frank Stein</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1885612291" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12753141116960570267">Orlando Figes is a social historian nonpareil. He can summon up the world of pre-revolutionary Russia like no writer I&apos;ve read. His descriptions of the peasant world of &quot;Icons and Cockroaches,&quot; of the Tsarist army where soldiers were whipped and had to memorize intricate addresses for every possible superior, of the socialist underground where the new intelligentsia embraced the &quot;cult of the bomb and the gun,&quot; where &quot;murder and the scaffold took on a magnetic charm,&quot; as one of their own said, al</span>
  <span id="freeText12753141116960570267" style="display:none">Orlando Figes is a social historian nonpareil. He can summon up the world of pre-revolutionary Russia like no writer I've read. His descriptions of the peasant world of "Icons and Cockroaches," of the Tsarist army where soldiers were whipped and had to memorize intricate addresses for every possible superior, of the socialist underground where the new intelligentsia embraced the "cult of the bomb and the gun," where "murder and the scaffold took on a magnetic charm," as one of their own said, all provide the reader with a stark picture of a society on the edge of destruction. <br /><br />The Russian revolution was a social revolution, so having such a historian trace the broad-based changes that happened in just a few years gives the reader an insight lacking in most histories of the event. Formerly quiescent peasant villages or "mirs" drove off the local squires, reappropriated their land, and formed little councils or "Soviets" managed by young, literate peasants, only to have these Soviets taken over by Bolshevik functionaries and turned into collective farms. The army itself became filled with soldier Soviets that voted on actions and leaders, only to have Trotsky and his Red Army re-establish the unquestioned dominance of the generals. The intelligentsia, such as the writer Maxim Gorky, that once celebrated the revolution watched their new overloads close down their presses and ban their books. Figes both shows how radical all types of Russians could be during the ferment, and how repressive and traditional the new Communist government was once it had attained power.<br /><br />The Russian revolution, of course, was not just an amorphous social revolt, but was shaped by a handful of powerful leaders on both sides, such as Tsar Nicholas and Alexandra, General Brusilov on the European Front, Lenin, Trotsky, the intellectual Social Revolutionary Chernov,the Menshevik opposition leader Martov, and many others. Figes has more trouble with these characters and with the straightforward narrative of the revolution. He cannot simply explain a story in chronological order, but must always veer back and forth across so many people and places the tale becomes impossible to follow. <br /><br />So parts of this book deserve all of the celebration it has received, while I wish others had a sharper editorial hand. I can say, however, there's nothing else out there like it, and that reading it is an amazing and worthwhile experience.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12753141116960570267" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


