<div id="review_2778715171" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2778715171" />
    <a title="K." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5663034-k"><img alt="K." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525318510p2/5663034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2778715171?book_show_action=true">Apr 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K." class="user" itemprop="url" name="K." href="/user/show/5663034-k">K.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=audience-adult">audience-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=setting-europe">setting-europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=difficult-topics">difficult-topics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=setting-asia">setting-asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5663034-k?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2778715171" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3878155385123501339">Trigger warnings: literally anything you can possibly think of, it&apos;s about the Russian Revolution... <br/><br/>I have been meaning to read this book for NINETEEN YEARS NOW. My year 12 history teacher read us some rather graphic excerpts that have been lodged in my brain since, like, August of 2000. So I finally picked it up and read it cover to cover, and frankly? I was a little disappointed. <br/><br/>Yes, it&apos;s a very detailed discussion of the Revolution and it would have taken a truly staggering amount of resear</span>
  <span id="freeText3878155385123501339" style="display:none">Trigger warnings: literally anything you can possibly think of, it's about the Russian Revolution... <br /><br />I have been meaning to read this book for NINETEEN YEARS NOW. My year 12 history teacher read us some rather graphic excerpts that have been lodged in my brain since, like, August of 2000. So I finally picked it up and read it cover to cover, and frankly? I was a little disappointed. <br /><br />Yes, it's a very detailed discussion of the Revolution and it would have taken a truly staggering amount of research to create this. But there are elements of it that felt repetitive and others that assumed a prior level of knowledge that I just flat out didn't have. <br /><br />Like I said, I've studied the Russian Revolution, so it's not like I was going in blind. But there's something about Figes' writing where he almost glosses over the roles of particular people and organisations as though the reader should either know who they are or remember who they are from 300 pages earlier. Nicholas II disappears from the story around page 350, and then pops up again on page 635. You'd think it would be pretty damned hard to forget who the Tsar was. And yet, when I finished a section about the Checka and the Left SRs and suddenly jumped to "After his abdication in March 1917, Nikolai Romanov (as he was now called)..."? I honestly went "Wait, who? Ohhhhhh." <br /><br />And that definitely wasn't the only time that happened. Maybe it was because I seemed to consistently pick this up after midnight and endeavour to read a 50-75 page chapter before turning the light out. Maybe it was because I'd built it up so much in my head over the past 19 years. But I mostly just found this...dry. Those gory bits my history teacher read us? Those were basically the most interesting sections in the entire book. Sigh... </span>
  <a data-text-id="3878155385123501339" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


