    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2692637949" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2692637949" />
    <a title="Jozef" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10170756-jozef"><img alt="Jozef" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581781318p2/10170756.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2692637949?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jozef" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jozef" href="/user/show/10170756-jozef">Jozef</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2692637949" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15741781360774574017">Well there goes my faith in humanity. <br/><br/>I thought the length of this book would be daunting, but it was actually very well paced and highly readable - what I wasn&apos;t prepared for was the emotional weight of it. Near the end of this book the author notes that 7 years of war had cheapened human life in Russia to the point of people simply ignoring dead bodies in the streets. Besides all the political aspects of this history, the reality on the ground is an onslaught of violence and human suffering. A</span>
  <span id="freeText15741781360774574017" style="display:none">Well there goes my faith in humanity. <br /><br />I thought the length of this book would be daunting, but it was actually very well paced and highly readable - what I wasn't prepared for was the emotional weight of it. Near the end of this book the author notes that 7 years of war had cheapened human life in Russia to the point of people simply ignoring dead bodies in the streets. Besides all the political aspects of this history, the reality on the ground is an onslaught of violence and human suffering. Approximately 10 million people die during this time, and a few of those are recounted in vivid detail. At that scope, it's horror beyond imagining.<br /><br />It doesn't help that the 30-odd years dealt with in this history are bookended by famine and Tsarist excesses on one side and more famine and Stalin's murderous regime on the other. No happy endings.<br /><br />Beyond the violence, this is a fascinating history to be sure, and many of the figures discussed (in good detail) here echo throughout history - the last Tsar Nicholas, the 'mad monk' Rasputin, the visionaries of Lenin, Trotsky, the idealists of Prince Lvov and Gorki, among many others are fascinating personalities and touch on so much of what makes not only Russia but humanity as a whole captivating. <br /><br />I've always wondered why communist icons and symbols are sold on the streets here in Berlin as tourist fodder, while Nazi symbols are banned outright. Both regimes are responsible for so much misery in the world that it seems odd to give the soviet symbols the green light. But then, at their core those Soviet symbols spawned from an ideology of hope and belief in something better, even if it was fated to morph into something terrible. Similarly, Lenin seems to get a free pass as "not that bad" despite being a dictator and his role in causing so much suffering - it seems that history can only smile on you when you are compared to the absolute worst tyrants to ever have lived.<br /><br />A people's tragedy was an excellent read and I feel it's also a very important one. As the passing of time entrenches foregone regimes deeper into the annals of history, we run the risk of isolating the ideal from the reality and forgetting just what regimes such as Soviet communism (and even fascism) really meant to live through. <br /><br />If we cannot collectively learn from the mistakes of the past, the suffering of so many people is rendered truly meaningless.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15741781360774574017" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

